author: @normanboyes4983
comment:
Thank you for this Max, it was very appropriate coverage which in the world, but more importantly Russia needs to see and understand. As things stand, your warnings go unheeded and the state sponsored criminality goes on unhindered (The execution of AZOZ POWS moved near the contact line from Mauripol).

I do not believe these people (all those responsible) will ever face justice for two reasons.

1. Post WW2 Germany was a defeated country who had unconditionally surrender. They effectively had no government and were subjected to administration by the Allies which then went on to arrange Nuremberg. But the key point is there was no German government apparatus to deploy propaganda to deny it ever happened. Of course it happened, but for many German people they could not accept or believe it happened even when all the evidence was presented.

2. When the Russian Government and its military fail in their mission in Ukraine and the troops come back home, the Russian Government will still exist, there will be no unconditional surrender and the propaganda machine will be intact as active as ever. How can Russia state administrate justice and war crimes courts when according to their version of events it never happened, was a deliberate provocation or the Ukrainian‚Äôs shelled themselves? How could the international community replicate some sort of Nuremberg process in these circumstances? Any proposal to do so would be vetoed by Russia and China in the UN and the Russian constitution does not allow extradition of Russian citizens.


The only possible way that criminal trials could take place is as follows. Once Russia withdraws its forces, the West needs to make clear to the Russian government that in order for sanctions to be lifted there is a timescale and conditions that must be met before a programme of winding them back even begins, with the caveat that sanctions will not be lifted until the west is satisfied that undertakings are achieved and not obstructed. The conditions are:

1. Russia agrees to the transfer of frozen assets that matches UN recognised rebuilding costs in Ukraine.
2. Russia agrees to fund any further funding shortfall (if the frozen assets are not enough) by equal annual payments over a period of ten years.
3. Russia agrees to extradite any citizen (no matter their status and rank) who has been indicted for War Crimes, to be extradited for trial at the International Criminal Court, amending its own constitution in order to achieve that.

It would need to be clear once the above have been agreed and undertakings given, sanctions would not be lifted immediately. Trust has to be rebuilt and as long as undertakings were demonstrably being fulfilled (evidence) the first sanctions could be lifted after 5 years and then in a logical evidence based ‚Äòreward‚Äô over the next 5 years.

author: @laboiteabonbons
comment:
Like it or not, but Russian war crimes seem to have long traditions.
My German grandmother fled in 1945 from Prussia from the Russian troops into the British-occupied part of Germany. The Prussian civilians still remembered how the Russian invasion was in World War 1 and, though they longed for liberation, were horrified by the arrival of the Russians. At the end of World War 2 some Germans were too old to flee or simply did not get away quickly enough. Together with stayed mayors and landlords they were executed or carried off. Many died on their way to Siberia. Wherever Russian soldiers met German civilians they pointed their guns on them and took their wristwatches and pocket watches in order to carry them home. There must have been thousands of German watches in Russia after the war. (Now it's Ukrainian microwave ovens and TV sets.) In 1945 any Russian soldier seemed to know three words of German: "Uhr" (watch) and "Frau, komm!" (Woman, come!). Russian soldiers raping German women was so common that German mothers cut the hair of their daughters short and dressed them like boys in order to protect them. As the Germans were the bad guys in this war and had committed their own war crimes, nobody accused those Russians. But how come that the Americans, British and French did not rape and steel during their liberation of Germany? The Americans gave chocolate and chewing gum to German kids.
America came with sugar and seduction whereas Russia came to spread fear and pain.
Ukraine is not Nazi-Germany! And though it looks like the Russian Army did not change a lot since those days.

Maxim, it would be nice if "all nazi criminals were caught and persecuted", but the sad truth is, most of them escaped ANY punishment (often with active assistance from German state), some of them got just a "slap on the wrist", and only VERY FEW got actually ("properly") punished - but even then, if you think of Eichman, or others like him, was there really any "reciprocity" or "parity" between his death, and the death of millions of Jews killed in the course of "die Endl√∂sung der Judenfrage"?

Also, while at it - I meant to point that out earlier, but never got around it. But now I got, so here we go:
The English translations for your videos are good and accurate, generally speaking - but sometimes got tad "patchy". In some instances the translator does an excellent job, like was the case in translating Russian expression "to sit on two chairs at the same time" into corresponding English idiom "to wear two hats", but in other instances he fails miserably - like, when he or she translates "–ø–ª–µ–Ω–Ω—ã–π" as "hostage" (it should be "POW", an abbreviation of "prisoner of war"), or making "carbon copy translations" (aka "word for word"), as was the case with "cannon meat" ("–ø—É—à–µ—á–Ω–æ–µ –º—è—Å–æ"). Yes, it is "technically correct", but English expression for those "myaso" is "cannon FODDER" (just like its German analogue/ source "Kanonefutter").
Yes, it might look like a nit-picking, and I'd agree that any English-speaking viewer can "make connection" and realise what the translator meant when he typed "cannon meat", but then I'm also pretty sure that majority of English viewers will got quite confused seeing CC reading "hostages" (instead of "POWs").

But those are not any serious critique, just "notes/ points for improvements". Your videos and comments are well done, concise and to the point. Keep up with a good work! ‚ÄúAll the photographs and video materials published by the Kiev regime, allegedly testifying to some kind of ‚Äúcrimes‚Äù by Russian military personnel in the city of Bucha, Kiev region, are another provocation.
